cs.CL, cs.LG, cs.AI, cs.NE, cs.CV 

This paper is about using a structured discriminator to learn a poetry generator that captures rhyming constraints. The paper focuses on natural language processing and machine learning techniques, which suggests that it is most likely to belong to the cs.CL (Computation and Language) category. The use of a generative adversarial setup also suggests that it could belong to the cs.LG (Learning) category. Additionally, the paper proposes a novel approach to learning rhyming patterns, which could fall under the cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) category. The use of a similarity matrix and the focus on capturing patterns in text could also suggest the paper belongs to the cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing) category. Finally, the paper mentions the use of computer vision techniques to visualize the generated poetry, which could suggest it belongs to the cs.CV (Computer Vision) category.
